Description: drop 'const' from the two file-local globals pointers
 1.10.4 stores the globals of test.c and lineedit.c behind a pointer declared
 `static struct statics *const ptr_to_statics`, forced into .data, and assigns it
 by casting the const away:
 .
     (*(struct statics**)&ptr_to_statics) = xzalloc(sizeof(S));
     barrier();
 .
 Writing an object defined with a const-qualified type is undefined behaviour, and
 gcc takes the declaration at its word: because the object is const, file-local and
 has no initialiser, every *read* of it is folded to its initial value, 0. The store
 above really happens, but the loads that follow never observe it. At -O0:
 .
     mov  %rax,(%rbx)        # the cast-away-const store
     mov  $0x0,%eax          # ptr_to_statics folded to the constant 0
     movl $0x0,0x8(%rax)     # first use of S -> writes through NULL -> SIGSEGV
 .
 This is not an optimisation artefact -- it reproduces at -O0, -O1, -O2 and -Os --
 so `barrier()` cannot help: gcc emits no load to reorder. The result is that the
 test/[ builtin of ash and hush segfaults on *every* invocation, including a bare
 `test`, and lineedit would fault the same way on its first use.
 .
 busybox's general globals mechanism is unaffected: include/libbb.h declares
 `extern struct globals *const ptr_to_globals`, and an extern object has no
 value the compiler may assume, so the same '*const' trick is safe there. Only
 these two file-local copies are miscompiled. Upstream reached the same place from
 the other side: 1.11.3 moved test.c's pointer to an `extern` declaration, and the
 crash is gone from 1.11.3 on. 1.8.3, which keeps plain writable statics with no
 pointer indirection, is likewise fine -- 1.10.4 is the only affected release.
 .
 Dropping `const` is the smallest change that removes both the undefined behaviour
 and gcc's licence to assume the value: the pointer stays in .data, the cast in
 INIT_S stays valid (now redundant), and the loads become real loads. The comment
 above each declaration is updated so it no longer claims what is no longer true.
Origin: vendor, shell-versions
Forwarded: not-needed

--- coreutils/test.c
+++ coreutils/test.c
@@ -167,9 +167,10 @@
 	jmp_buf leaving;
 };
 
-/* Make it reside in writable memory, yet make compiler understand
- * that it is not going to change. */
-static struct statics *const ptr_to_statics __attribute__ ((section (".data")));
+/* Make it reside in writable memory. NOT const: this pointer is assigned at
+ * runtime, and a const object gcc may fold to its initialiser (0) on every read.
+ */
+static struct statics *ptr_to_statics __attribute__ ((section (".data")));
 
 #define S (*ptr_to_statics)
 #define t_wp            (S.t_wp         )
--- libbb/lineedit.c
+++ libbb/lineedit.c
@@ -120,9 +120,10 @@
 #endif
 };
 
-/* Make it reside in writable memory, yet make compiler understand
- * that it is not going to change. */
-static struct statics *const ptr_to_statics __attribute__ ((section (".data")));
+/* Make it reside in writable memory. NOT const: this pointer is assigned at
+ * runtime, and a const object gcc may fold to its initialiser (0) on every read.
+ */
+static struct statics *ptr_to_statics __attribute__ ((section (".data")));
 
 #define S (*ptr_to_statics)
 #define state            (S.state           )
